Subject:Re: [Antenna-discussion] ferrite rod antenna for a crystal radio
	A 75 foot inverted L works just dandy.  But a good ground is also essentia=
l.

On Oct 30, 2012, at 3:24 PM, boswell alan <alan.boswell@blueyonder.co.uk> w=
rote:

> Kirk
> =

> Alas, that suggested ferrite rod also has a very large reactance which
> produces a large tuning/matching problem that needs addressing, so I
> suspect the capture area might be below what you have predicted.
> =

> But that raises an interesting possibility of very long ferrite rods
> of the sort sometimes used to receive ELF signals, that is signals in
> the range 10-100 Hz, plus or minus.  One of them in the literature had
> 300,000 turns on the coil.  A practical problem is that ferrite is
> likely to be more brittle than most materials used to support it.
> That kind of antenna is tuned and the bandwidth is extremely small :)
> =

> Crystal set users do not ALL use 75-metre masts, quite a lot of them
> use much more modest antennas, and anything over 20-30 ft should work
> reasonably well, and inverted-L antennas work all right in this
> application.
> =

> Alan G3NOQ
> =

> =

> =

> =

> =

